imbledon champions (pre-Open Era)]]\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:1994 deaths]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in men's singles]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in mixed doubles]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in men's doubles]]\n[[Category:Deaths from leukemia]]\n[[Category:Professional tennis players before the Open Era]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in boys' singles]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in boys' doubles]]\n", "name_user": "Tennisedu", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProfessional career: 1957\u20131966:Tennisedu/space", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lew_Hoad"}
{"title_page": "Justin Brake (journalist)", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian journalist}}\n\n'''Justin Brake''' is a Canadian journalist and winner of a 2019 press freedom case in [[Newfoundland and Labrador]].  Brake was the first Canadian journalist to face both criminal and civil charges.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/journalist-charged-in-criminal-civil-courts-wins-press-freedom-prize|title=Journalist charged in criminal, civil courts wins press freedom prize {{!}} Ottawa Citizen|last=May 3|first=Maggie Parkhill Updated|last2=2018|date=2018-05-03|website=ottawacitizen.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nationalobserver.com/2018/05/03/news/facing-jail-time-journalist-justin-brake-says-courts-being-used-protect-corporate|title=Facing jail time, journalist Justin Brake says the courts being used to protect corporate projects|last=Meyer|first=Carl|date=May 3, 2018|work=National Observer|access-date=}}</ref> He won the civil case, while the criminal charges are still pending. Legal experts and press freedom groups such as Canadian Journalists for Free Expression, the Canadian Association of Journalists feared that if the charges were upheld it would give precedence to property rights over media rights as defined in case law and the Charter of Rights and Freedoms.<ref name=\"cjfe.org\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cjfe.org/this_is_a_serious_threat_to_press_freedom|title=Charges Against Justin Brake Are A Serious Threat to Press Freedom|website=CJFE {{!}} Canadian Journalists for Free Expression|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://caj.ca/blog/court_victory_for_Justin_Brake|title=COURT VICTORY FOR JUSTIN BRAKE, JOURNALISM|website=caj.ca|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://caj.ca/blog/court_victory_for_Justin_Brake|title=Court Victory for Justin Brake, Journalism|last=Speckart|first=Kathleen|date=March 28, 2019|website=Canadian Association of Journalists|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thecourt.ca/breaking-the-news-what-the-cases-of-marie-maude-denis-and-justin-brake-could-mean-for-journalism/|title=Breaking the News: What the Cases of Marie-Maude Denis and Justin Brake Could Mean for Journalism|last=Beatson|first=Jesse|date=Jan 30, 2019|work=The Court|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cjfe.org/arrest_warrant_issued_for_journalist_covering_muskrat_falls_must_be_rescinded|title=Court order threatening arrest of journalist covering Muskrat Falls must be rescinded|website=CJFE {{!}} Canadian Journalists for Free Expression|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref><ref name=\"cjfe.org\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://caj.ca/blog.php?id=64&bypassCookie=1|title=Canadian Association of Journalists|website=caj.ca|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.halifaxexaminer.ca/featured/criminal-charges-against-justin-brake-are-an-attack-on-press-freedom-morning-file-monday-march-13-2017/|title=Criminal charges against Justin Brake are an attack on press freedom|last=Bousquet|first=Tim|date=March 13, 2017|work=Halifax Examiner|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thetyee.ca/Mediacheck/2019/05/10/In-Awe-Fragile-Free-Press/|title=In Awe of the Fragile Free Press|last=Smith|first=Andrea|date=May 10, 2019|work=TheTyee.ca|access-date=}}</ref> The case also drew international attention from the Fahmy Foundation,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fahmyfoundation.org/justin-brake.html|title=The Fahmy Foundation|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> [[Reporters without Borders]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rsf.org/en/news/canada-rsf-condemns-criminal-charges-against-journalist-covering-protests-muskrat-falls|title=Canada - RSF condemns criminal charges against journalist covering protests in Muskrat Falls {{!}} Reporters without borders|date=2017-03-09|website=RSF|language=en|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> and was cited as a concern by the [[Press Freedom Index]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://j-source.ca/article/canada-back-in-the-top-20-of-world-press-freedom-index-but-concerns-remain/|title=Canada back in the top 20 of World Press Freedom Index - but concerns remain.|last=WATSON|first=H.G.|date=|work=Ryerson Review of Journalism|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.commondreams.org/news/2018/03/23/affront-freedom-press-canadian-journalist-faces-criminal-charges-covering-protest|title='Affront to Freedom of the Press,' Canadian Journalist Faces Criminal Charges for Covering Protest|last=Conley|first=Julia|date=March 23, 2018|work=Common Dreams|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.winnipegfreepress.com/opinion/analysis/press-freedom-under-siege-at-home-and-abroad-509044462.html|title=Press freedom under siege, at home and abroad|last=Sampert|first=Shannon|date=April 25, 2019|work=Winnipeg Free Press|access-date=}}</ref> The 29-page unanimous decision by the [[Supreme Court of Newfoundland and Labrador (Court of Appeal)|Court of Appeal of Newfoundland and Labrador]], established an important legal precedent across Canada protecting the legal rights of media against useof [[injunctions]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-in-landmark-decision-newfoundland-appeal-court-judge-lays-out/|title=In landmark decision, Newfoundland appeal court judge lays out criteria for journalist protections when reporting at protests|last=Leeder|first=Jessica|date=March 28, 2019|work=The Globe and Mail|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://aptnnews.ca/2019/03/28/justin-brakes-case-a-win-for-journalistic-freedom/|title=Justin Brakes Case a Victory for journalistic Freedom|last=Martens|first=Kathleen|date=March 28, 2019|work=APTN|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Lockett|first=Monica|date=2020|title=A Duty to Report: Alternative Journalism as Political Obligation to Resist and Remedy Injustice|url=https://digitalcommons.library.tru.ca/phpdialogues/vol2/iss1/|journal=PHP Dialogues Dialogues: Undergraduate Research in Philosophy, History, and Politics|volume= 2 , Article 1|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nBrake was the recipient of the 20th annual Press Freedom Award, awarded annually by the Canadian Committee for World Press Freedom,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-journalist-justin-brake-charged-over-muskrat-falls-reporting-wins/|title=Journalist Justin Brake, charged over Muskrat Falls reporting, wins Press Freedom Award|last=THE CANADIAN PRESS|first=|date=May 3, 2018|work=Globe and Mail|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cpac.ca/en/programs/primetime-politics/episodes/61893760/episode-still-from-media-server-34473/|title=Justin Brake on World Press Freedom Day|last=|first=|date=May 3, 2018|work=CPAC|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ipolitics.ca/article/following-the-story-ipolitics-qa-with-justin-brake/|title=Following the story: iPolitics' Q&A with Justin Brake|last=Turnbull|first=|date=May 4, 201|work=ipolitics|access-date=}}</ref> the 2018 PEN Canada/Ken Filkow Prize for freedom of expression,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pencanada.ca/news/pen-awards-annual-filkow-prize-to-journalist-justin-brake/|title=Justin Brake wins 2018 PEN Canada/Ken Filkow Prize for freedom of expression|date=2018-06-07|website=PEN Canada|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref> and co-recipient, with Indigenous journalist [[Karyn Pugliese]], of the 2019 Elias Boudinot Free Press Award, issued by the [[Native American Journalists Association]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://najanewsroom.com/2019/06/21/naja-announces-recipients-of-2019-free-press-investigative-awards/|title=NAJA announces recipients of 2019 free press, investigative awards|last=scospernajacom|date=2019-06-21|website=Native American Journalists Association|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nBrake was born in [[Newfoundland]] and raised in [[Ottawa]]; he does not identify as being indigenous, but says he has some [[Mi\ua78ckmaq]] ancestry.<ref>{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-journalist-faces-unprecedented-criminal-charges-over-coverage-of/ | title=Journalist faces unprecedented criminal charges over coverage of Muskrat Falls protest | author=Jessica Leider | date=22 March 2018 | accessdate=8 January 2020 | newspaper=[[The Globe and Mail]]}}</ref> Brake graduated from [[Algonquin College]] in Ottawa in 2001.\n\n== Career ==\nFrom 2012 to 2017, Brake was a journalist at ''[[The Independent (Newfoundland)|The Independent]]'' based in Newfoundland and Labrador.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hanrahan|first=Maura|date=|title=A Story of Invisibility: The Reaction of the Print Media to the Formation of Qalipu Mi'kmaq First Nation.|url=https://web.a.ebscohost.com/abstract?direct=true&profile=ehost&scope=site&authtype=crawler&jrnl=0831585X&AN=101983671&h=UQculu7%2bxBHdIydIir8jiTVCRpuVaQD7n7l27Il4qu5P066vVXU%2fHrgln7aZemZn8DlzTLZA3j5jb4%2bGQH3U6Q%3d%3d&crl=c&resultNs=AdminWebAuth&resultLocal=ErrCrlNotAuth&crlhashurl=login.aspx%3fdirect%3dtrue%26profile%3dehost%26scope%3dsite%26authtype%3dcrawler%26jrnl%3d0831585X%26AN%3d101983671|journal=Source: Native Studies Review|volume=. 2012, Vol. 21 Issue 1|pages=61\u201382|via=}}</ref> In 2017, he joined [[APTN National News|APTN News]] as a reporter, and works in their Ottawa bureau.\n\n=== Muskrat Falls ===\n[[Lower Churchill Project|Muskrat Falls]] is a natural 15 metre [[waterfall]] located on the lower [[Churchill River (Atlantic)|Churchill River]] about 25 kilometers west of [[Happy Valley-Goose Bay, Newfoundland and Labrador|Happy Valley-Goose Bay]], [[Labrador]] with great [[hydropower]] potential. From 1970 to the present plans were put in place to develop hydro-electricity. This includes development known as the [[Lower Churchill Project]], which has raised concerns of scientists and local Inuit about methyl-mercury poisoning of the water, wildlife and food sources.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/j5zbpx/how-activists-are-resisting-a-megadam-that-threatens-cultural-genocide|title=Why Indigenous Activists Are Resisting This Hydroelectricity Project|last=Olsen|first=Deidre|date=2018-12-07|website=Vice|language=en|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref> Local Indigenous groups say they ere not properly consulted before the project began, and hosted a series of demonstrations against the project, including hunger strikes in 2013.  The Nunatsiavut Government, which represents the Inuit of Labrador, was unsuccessful in using the courts to try and halt the project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aptnnews.ca/2019/08/10/public-inquiry-hears-from-people-living-in-fear-as-muskrat-falls-flooding-begins/|title=Public inquiry hears from people living in fear as Muskrat Falls flooding begins - APTN NewsAPTN News|website=aptnnews.ca|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref>\n\n==== Civil charges ====\nIn October 2016, Brake was covering the Muskrat Falls story for ''The Independent.'' Indigenous demonstrators, who call themselves land and water protectors, broke a lock on October 22 and entered the property of Nalcor Energy. Brake followed the protesters filming and documenting what happened to them over the course of several days. He was the sole reporter inside the facility.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/article-canada-isnt-the-leader-on-press-freedoms-that-we-think-we-are/|title=Canada isn't the leader on press freedoms that we think it is|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref>  When Nalcor filed and was granted an injunction to get the demonstrators off the property, they listed Brake on the injunction without mentioning that he was a journalist and not part of the protest. Brake was charged criminally with mischief and disobeying a court order and with civil contempt proceedings in [[Supreme Court of Newfoundland and Labrador|Newfoundland and Labrador Supreme Court]], because he'd been present on the property.<ref name=\"aptnnews.ca\">{{Cite web|url=https://aptnnews.ca/2019/03/28/justin-brakes-case-a-win-for-journalistic-freedom/|title=Court decision a victory for journalists covering Indigenous protests - APTN NewsAPTN News|website=aptnnews.ca|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref> The injunction was issued on October 16, 2016 and an ex parte contempt appearance order issued on October 24, 2016.<ref>https://records.court.nl.ca/public/supremecourt/decisiondownload/?decision-id=5521&mode=stream</ref> At least one local rally was held in support of Brake demanding the charges be dropped.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/newfoundland-labrador/justin-brake-independent-rally-1.4041257|title=Rally calls for charges against Independent editor Justin Brake to be dropped|last=MacEachern|first=Daniel|date=March 25, 2017|work=CBC|access-date=}}</ref> Brake fought the civil charges but lost. On March 15, 2017, Justice George Murphy of the Supreme Court of Newfoundland and Labrador wrote in his decision: \u201cMr. Brake\u2019s status as a journalist was not a material fact and there was no obligation on Nalcor to bring that fact to the attention of the Court on their application for the Injunction Order or the Contempt Appearance Order.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cjfe.org/supreme_court_ruling_in_brake_case_shows_failure_to_protect_the_public_interest|title=Ruling in Brake Civil Case Highlights Failure to Protect the Public Interest|website=CJFE {{!}} Canadian Journalists for Free Expression|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canadalandshow.com/judge-rules-no-special-status-for-journalist-covering-protest/|title=Judge: No Special Status For Journalist Charged For Covering Protest|website=www.canadalandshow.com|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref>\n\n==== The Court of Appeal====\nThe case was appealed to the Court of Appeal of Newfoundland and Labrador, the province's highest court December 12, 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetelegram.com/news/local/journalist-justin-brakes-case-heard-in-court-of-appeal-169740/|title=Journalist Justin Brake's case heard in Court of Appeal|last=Bradbury|first=Tara|date=Dec 12, 2017|work=|access-date=}}</ref>[[Aboriginal Peoples Television Network|APTN]] intervened in the case and Pugliese, then the executive director of news, testified personally, arguing media to be present at conflicts involving Indigenous Peoples,  with reference to the calls to action of Canada's [[Truth and Reconciliation Commission of Canada|Truth and Reconciliation Commission]], which had submitted its final report in December 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nctr.ca/reports2.php|title=Reports {{!}} NCTR|website=nctr.ca|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://j-source.ca/article/what-justin-brakes-recent-win-means-for-press-freedom-in-2019/|title=What Justin Brake's recent win means for press freedom in 2019|last=ago|first=Grant Buckler \u2022 8 months|date=2019-04-04|website=JSource|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref> In [https://records.court.nl.ca/public/supremecourt/decisiondownload/?decision-id=5521&mode=stream his decision] issued March 28, 2019 Justice Derek Green stated: \u201cThe evidence from ''APTN'', which I accept, is that Aboriginal communities have been historically under-represented in the Canadian media.\u201d<ref name=\"aptnnews.ca\"/> The decision referenced both the [[Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms|Charter rights]] to free expression for journalists and stated the need for reconciliation \u201cplaces a heightened importance on ensuring that independently-reported information about (A)boriginal issues, including (A)boriginal protests, is available to the extent possible.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://j-source.ca/article/what-justin-brakes-recent-win-means-for-press-freedom-in-2019/|title=What Justin Brake's recent win means for press freedom in 2019|last=ago|first=Grant Buckler \u2022 8 months|date=2019-04-04|website=JSource|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref> Nalcour did not appeal the case to the Supreme Court of Canada. The case established an important legal precedent for press freedom. It prevents the arbitrary use of injunctions against journalists and recognizes the important role journalists have in covering protests and Indigenous issues in Canada.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Davidson|first=Terry|title=Protest injunctions must indicate presence of journalists, lawyers say following appeal decision Thursday|url=https://www.thelawyersdaily.ca/articles/11421|journal=The Lawyer's Daily|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|chapter=Book Reviews Published in the Globe and Mail|date=2009-01-31|publisher=University of Toronto Press|isbn=978-1-4426-8767-7|doi=10.3138/9781442687677-050|title=Collected Works of George Grant}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://toronto.citynews.ca/2019/03/29/landmark-n-l-ruling-defends-press-freedom-and-coverage-of-indigenous-issues/|title=Landmark N.L. ruling defends press freedom and coverage of Indigenous issues|last=McKenzie-Sutter|first=Holly|date=March 29, 2019|work=Canadian Press|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==== Criminal charges ====\nAs of September 2019, lawyers for the crown filed criminal charges of mischief and unlawfully disobeying an order of the court against Brake even though the charges were based on the same set of facts which Justice Green had dismissed in the civil case.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/newfoundland-labrador/justine-brake-not-guilty-plea-1.5228940|title=Reporter pleads not guilty to charges stemming from Muskrat Falls protest coverage|last=|first=|date=Jul 29, 2019|work=CBC|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ca.news.yahoo.com/lawyer-justin-brake-asks-judge-013214397.html|title=Lawyer for Justin Brake asks judge to dismiss criminal charge against reporter|website=ca.news.yahoo.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> In the September court appearance Brake filed a charter challenge to ask for a stay of proceedings, and Brake's lawyer Geoff Budden said he would be arguing the charges are an \"abuse of process.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ca.news.yahoo.com/reporter-justin-brake-mounting-charter-193432850.html|title=Reporter Justin Brake mounting charter challenge against Muskrat Falls charges|website=ca.news.yahoo.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref>  In November 2019 the Crown decided to drop the charge against Brake of unlawfully disobeying an order of the court, but decided to pursue a charge of mischief over $5,000. Judge Phyllis Harris will decide if the case proceeds.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/newfoundland-labrador/justin-brake-application-geoff-budden-1.5351309|title=Lawyer for Justin Brake asks judge to dismiss criminal charge against reporter|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brake, Justin}}\n[[Category:Canadian newspaper journalists]]\n[[Category:Freedom of the press by country]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Algonquin College alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian journalist}}\n\n'''Justin Brake''' is a Canadian journalist and winner of a 2019 press freedom case in [[Newfoundland and Labrador]].  Brake was the first Canadian journalist to face both criminal and civil charges.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/journalist-charged-in-criminal-civil-courts-wins-press-freedom-prize|title=Journalist charged in criminal, civil courts wins press freedom prize {{!}} Ottawa Citizen|last=May 3|first=Maggie Parkhill Updated|last2=2018|date=2018-05-03|website=ottawacitizen.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nationalobserver.com/2018/05/03/news/facing-jail-time-journalist-justin-brake-says-courts-being-used-protect-corporate|title=Facing jail time, journalist Justin Brake says the courts being used to protect corporate projects|last=Meyer|first=Carl|date=May 3, 2018|work=National Observer|access-date=}}</ref> He won the civil case, while the criminal charges are still pending. Legal experts and press freedom groups such as Canadian Journalists for Free Expression, the Canadian Association of Journalists feared that if the charges were upheld it would give precedence to property rights over media rights as defined in case law and the Charter of Rights and Freedoms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cjfe.org/this_is_a_serious_threat_to_press_freedom|title=Charges Against Justin Brake Are A Serious Threat to Press Freedom|website=CJFE {{!}} Canadian Journalists for Free Expression|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://caj.ca/blog/court_victory_for_Justin_Brake|title=COURT VICTORY FOR JUSTIN BRAKE, JOURNALISM|website=caj.ca|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://caj.ca/blog/court_victory_for_Justin_Brake|title=Court Victory for Justin Brake, Journalism|last=Speckart|first=Kathleen|date=March 28, 2019|website=Canadian Association of Journalists|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thecourt.ca/breaking-the-news-what-the-cases-of-marie-maude-denis-and-justin-brake-could-mean-for-journalism/|title=Breaking the News: What the Cases of Marie-Maude Denis and Justin Brake Could Mean for Journalism|last=Beatson|first=Jesse|date=Jan 30, 2019|work=The Court|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cjfe.org/arrest_warrant_issued_for_journalist_covering_muskrat_falls_must_be_rescinded|title=Court order threatening arrest of journalist covering Muskrat Falls must be rescinded|website=CJFE {{!}} Canadian Journalists for Free Expression|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cjfe.org/this_is_a_serious_threat_to_press_freedom|title=Charges Against Justin Brake Are A Serious Threat to Press Freedom|website=CJFE {{!}} Canadian Journalists for Free Expression|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://caj.ca/blog.php?id=64&bypassCookie=1|title=Canadian Association of Journalists|website=caj.ca|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.halifaxexaminer.ca/featured/criminal-charges-against-justin-brake-are-an-attack-on-press-freedom-morning-file-monday-march-13-2017/|title=Criminal charges against Justin Brake are an attack on press freedom|last=Bousquet|first=Tim|date=March 13, 2017|work=Halifax Examiner|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thetyee.ca/Mediacheck/2019/05/10/In-Awe-Fragile-Free-Press/|title=In Awe of the Fragile Free Press|last=Smith|first=Andrea|date=May 10, 2019|work=TheTyee.ca|access-date=}}</ref> The case also drew international attention from the Fahmy Foundation,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fahmyfoundation.org/justin-brake.html|title=The Fahmy Foundation|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> [[Reporters without Borders]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rsf.org/en/news/canada-rsf-condemns-criminal-charges-against-journalist-covering-protests-muskrat-falls|title=Canada - RSF condemns criminal charges against journalist covering protests in Muskrat Falls {{!}} Reporters without borders|date=2017-03-09|website=RSF|language=en|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> and was cited as a concern by the [[Press Freedom Index]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://j-source.ca/article/canada-back-in-the-top-20-of-world-press-freedom-index-but-concerns-remain/|title=Canada back in the top 20 of World Press Freedom Index - but concerns remain.|last=WATSON|first=H.G.|date=|work=Ryerson Review of Journalism|access-date=}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.commondreams.org/news/2018/03/23/affront-freedom-press-canadian-journalist-faces-criminal-charges-covering-protest|title='Affront to Freedom of the Press,' Canadian Journalist Faces Criminal Charges for Covering Protest|last=Conley|first=Julia|date=March 23, 2018|work=Common Dreams|access-date=}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.winnipegfreepress.com/opinion/analysis/press-freedom-under-siege-at-home-and-abroad-509044462.html|title=Press freedom under siege, at home and abroad|last=Sampert|first=Shannon|date=April 25, 2019|work=Winnipeg Free Press|access-date=}}</ref> The 29-page unanimous decision by the [[Supreme Court of Newfoundland and Labrador (Court of Appeal)|Court of Appeal of Newfoundland and Labrador]], established an important legal precedent across Canada protecting the legal rights of media against useof [[injunctions]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-in-landmark-decision-newfoundland-appeal-court-judge-lays-out/|title=In landmark decision, Newfoundland appeal court judge lays out criteria for journalist protections when reporting at protests|last=Leeder|first=Jessica|date=March 28, 2019|work=The Globe and Mail|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://aptnnews.ca/2019/03/28/justin-brakes-case-a-win-for-journalistic-freedom/|title=Justin Brakes Case a Victory for journalistic Freedom|last=Martens|first=Kathleen|date=March 28, 2019|work=APTN|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Lockett|first=Monica|date=2020|title=A Duty to Report: Alternative Journalism as Political Obligation to Resist and Remedy Injustice|url=https://digitalcommons.library.tru.ca/phpdialogues/vol2/iss1/|journal=PHP Dialogues Dialogues: Undergraduate Research in Philosophy, History, and Politics|volume=Vol. 2 , Article 1|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nBrake was the recipient of the 20th annual Press Freedom Award, awarded annually by the Canadian Committee for World Press Freedom,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-journalist-justin-brake-charged-over-muskrat-falls-reporting-wins/|title=Journalist Justin Brake, charged over Muskrat Falls reporting, wins Press Freedom Award|last=THE CANADIAN PRESS|first=|date=May 3, 2018|work=Globe and Mail|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cpac.ca/en/programs/primetime-politics/episodes/61893760/episode-still-from-media-server-34473/|title=Justin Brake on World Press Freedom Day|last=|first=|date=May 3, 2018|work=CPAC|access-date=}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ipolitics.ca/article/following-the-story-ipolitics-qa-with-justin-brake/|title=Following the story: iPolitics' Q&A with Justin Brake|last=Turnbull|first=|date=May 4, 201|work=ipolitics|access-date=}}</ref> the 2018 PEN Canada/Ken Filkow Prize for freedom of expression,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pencanada.ca/news/pen-awards-annual-filkow-prize-to-journalist-justin-brake/|title=Justin Brake wins 2018 PEN Canada/Ken Filkow Prize for freedom of expression|date=2018-06-07|website=PEN Canada|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref> and co-recipient, with Indigenous journalist [[Karyn Pugliese]], of the 2019 Elias Boudinot Free Press Award, issued by the [[Native American Journalists Association]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://najanewsroom.com/2019/06/21/naja-announces-recipients-of-2019-free-press-investigative-awards/|title=NAJA announces recipients of 2019 free press, investigative awards|last=scospernajacom|date=2019-06-21|website=Native American Journalists Association|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref> \n\n== Early life and education ==\nBrake was born in [[Newfoundland]] and raised in [[Ottawa]]; he does not identify as being indigenous, but says he has some [[Mi\ua78ckmaq]] ancestry.<ref>{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-journalist-faces-unprecedented-criminal-charges-over-coverage-of/ | title=Journalist faces unprecedented criminal charges over coverage of Muskrat Falls protest | author=Jessica Leider | date=22 March 2018 | accessdate=8 January 2020 | newspaper=[[The Globe and Mail]]}}</ref> Brake graduated from [[Algonquin College]] in Ottawa in 2001.\n\n== Career ==\nFrom 2012 to 2017, Brake was a journalist at ''[[The Independent (Newfoundland)|The Independent]]'' based in Newfoundland and Labrador.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hanrahan|first=Maura|date=|title=A Story of Invisibility: The Reaction of the Print Media to the Formation of Qalipu Mi'kmaq First Nation.|url=https://web.a.ebscohost.com/abstract?direct=true&profile=ehost&scope=site&authtype=crawler&jrnl=0831585X&AN=101983671&h=UQculu7%2bxBHdIydIir8jiTVCRpuVaQD7n7l27Il4qu5P066vVXU%2fHrgln7aZemZn8DlzTLZA3j5jb4%2bGQH3U6Q%3d%3d&crl=c&resultNs=AdminWebAuth&resultLocal=ErrCrlNotAuth&crlhashurl=login.aspx%3fdirect%3dtrue%26profile%3dehost%26scope%3dsite%26authtype%3dcrawler%26jrnl%3d0831585X%26AN%3d101983671|journal=Source: Native Studies Review|volume=. 2012, Vol. 21 Issue 1|pages=61\u201382|via=}}</ref> In 2017, he joined [[APTN National News|APTN News]] as a reporter, and works in their Ottawa bureau.\n\n=== Muskrat Falls ===\n[[Lower Churchill Project|Muskrat Falls]] is a natural 15 metre [[waterfall]] located on the lower [[Churchill River (Atlantic)|Churchill River]] about 25 kilometers west of [[Happy Valley-Goose Bay, Newfoundland and Labrador|Happy Valley-Goose Bay]], [[Labrador]] with great [[hydropower]] potential. From 1970 to the present plans were put in place to develop hydro-electricity. This includes development known as the [[Lower Churchill Project]], which has raised concerns of scientists and local Inuit about methyl-mercury poisoning of the water, wildlife and food sources.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/j5zbpx/how-activists-are-resisting-a-megadam-that-threatens-cultural-genocide|title=Why Indigenous Activists Are Resisting This Hydroelectricity Project|last=Olsen|first=Deidre|date=2018-12-07|website=Vice|language=en|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref> Local Indigenous groups say they ere not properly consulted before the project began, and hosted a series of demonstrations against the project, including hunger strikes in 2013.  The Nunatsiavut Government, which represents the Inuit of Labrador, was unsuccessful in using the courts to try and halt the project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aptnnews.ca/2019/08/10/public-inquiry-hears-from-people-living-in-fear-as-muskrat-falls-flooding-begins/|title=Public inquiry hears from people living in fear as Muskrat Falls flooding begins - APTN NewsAPTN News|website=aptnnews.ca|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref>\n\n==== Civil charges ====\nIn October 2016, Brake was covering the Muskrat Falls story for ''The Independent.'' Indigenous demonstrators, who call themselves land and water protectors, broke a lock on October 22 and entered the property of Nalcor Energy. Brake followed the protesters filming and documenting what happened to them over the course of several days. He was the sole reporter inside the facility.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/article-canada-isnt-the-leader-on-press-freedoms-that-we-think-we-are/|title=Canada isn't the leader on press freedoms that we think it is|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref>  When Nalcor filed and was granted an injunction to get the demonstrators off the property, they listed Brake on the injunction without mentioning that he was a journalist and not part of the protest. Brake was charged criminally with mischief and disobeying a court order and with civil contempt proceedings in [[Supreme Court of Newfoundland and Labrador|Newfoundland and Labrador Supreme Court]], because he'd been present on the property.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aptnnews.ca/2019/03/28/justin-brakes-case-a-win-for-journalistic-freedom/|title=Court decision a victory for journalists covering Indigenous protests - APTN NewsAPTN News|website=aptnnews.ca|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref> The injunction was issued on October 16, 2016 and an ex parte contempt appearance order issued on October, 24, 2016.<ref>https://records.court.nl.ca/public/supremecourt/decisiondownload/?decision-id=5521&mode=stream</ref> At least one local rally was held in support of Brake demanding the charges be dropped.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/newfoundland-labrador/justin-brake-independent-rally-1.4041257|title=Rally calls for charges against Independent editor Justin Brake to be dropped|last=MacEachern|first=Daniel|date=March 25, 2017|work=CBC|access-date=}}</ref> Brake fought the civil charges but lost. On March 15, 2017, Justice George Murphy of the Supreme Court of Newfoundland and Labrador wrote in his decision: \u201cMr. Brake\u2019s status as a journalist was not a material fact and there was no obligation on Nalcor to bring that fact to the attention of the Court on their application for the Injunction Order or the Contempt Appearance Order.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cjfe.org/supreme_court_ruling_in_brake_case_shows_failure_to_protect_the_public_interest|title=Ruling in Brake Civil Case Highlights Failure to Protect the Public Interest|website=CJFE {{!}} Canadian Journalists for Free Expression|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canadalandshow.com/judge-rules-no-special-status-for-journalist-covering-protest/|title=Judge: No Special Status For Journalist Charged For Covering Protest|website=www.canadalandshow.com|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref>\n\n==== The Court of Appeal====\nThe case was appealed to the Court of Appeal of Newfoundland and Labrador, the province's highest court December 12, 2017. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetelegram.com/news/local/journalist-justin-brakes-case-heard-in-court-of-appeal-169740/|title=Journalist Justin Brake's case heard in Court of Appeal|last=Bradbury|first=Tara|date=Dec 12, 2017|work=|access-date=}}</ref>[[Aboriginal Peoples Television Network|APTN]] intervened in the case and Pugliese, then the executive director of news, testified personally, arguing media to be present at conflicts involving Indigenous Peoples,  with reference to the calls to action of Canada's [[Truth and Reconciliation Commission of Canada|Truth and Reconciliation Commission]], which had submitted its final report in December 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nctr.ca/reports2.php|title=Reports {{!}} NCTR|website=nctr.ca|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://j-source.ca/article/what-justin-brakes-recent-win-means-for-press-freedom-in-2019/|title=What Justin Brake's recent win means for press freedom in 2019|last=ago|first=Grant Buckler \u2022 8 months|date=2019-04-04|website=JSource|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref> In [https://records.court.nl.ca/public/supremecourt/decisiondownload/?decision-id=5521&mode=stream his decision] issued March 28, 2019 Justice Derek Green stated: \u201cThe evidence from ''APTN'', which I accept, is that Aboriginal communities have been historically under-represented in the Canadian media.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aptnnews.ca/2019/03/28/justin-brakes-case-a-win-for-journalistic-freedom/|title=Court decision a victory for journalists covering Indigenous protests - APTN NewsAPTN News|website=aptnnews.ca|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref> The decision referenced both the [[Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms|Charter rights]] to free expression for journalists and stated the need for reconciliation \u201cplaces a heightened importance on ensuring that independently-reported information about (A)boriginal issues, including (A)boriginal protests, is available to the extent possible.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://j-source.ca/article/what-justin-brakes-recent-win-means-for-press-freedom-in-2019/|title=What Justin Brake's recent win means for press freedom in 2019|last=ago|first=Grant Buckler \u2022 8 months|date=2019-04-04|website=JSource|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref> Nalcour did not appeal the case to the Supreme Court of Canada. The case established an important legal precedent for press freedom. It prevents the arbitrary use of injunctions against journalists and recognizes the important role journalists have in covering protests and Indigenous issues in Canada.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Davidson|first=Terry|title=Protest injunctions must indicate presence of journalists, lawyers say following appeal decision Thursday|url=https://www.thelawyersdaily.ca/articles/11421|journal=The Lawyer's Daily|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|chapter=Book Reviews Published in the Globe and Mail|date=2009-01-31|publisher=University of Toronto Press|isbn=978-1-4426-8767-7|doi=10.3138/9781442687677-050|title=Collected Works of George Grant}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://toronto.citynews.ca/2019/03/29/landmark-n-l-ruling-defends-press-freedom-and-coverage-of-indigenous-issues/|title=Landmark N.L. ruling defends press freedom and coverage of Indigenous issues|last=McKenzie-Sutter|first=Holly|date=March 29, 2019|work=Canadian Press|access-date=}}</ref> \n\n==== Criminal charges ====\nAs of September 2019, lawyers for the crown filed criminal charges of mischief and unlawfully disobeying an order of the court against Brake even though the charges were based on the same set of facts which Justice Green had dismissed in the civil case.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/newfoundland-labrador/justine-brake-not-guilty-plea-1.5228940|title=Reporter pleads not guilty to charges stemming from Muskrat Falls protest coverage|last=|first=|date=Jul 29, 2019|work=CBC|access-date=}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ca.news.yahoo.com/lawyer-justin-brake-asks-judge-013214397.html|title=Lawyer for Justin Brake asks judge to dismiss criminal charge against reporter|website=ca.news.yahoo.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> In the September court appearance Brake filed a charter challenge to ask for a stay of proceedings, and Brake's lawyer Geoff Budden said he would be arguing the charges are an \"abuse of process.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ca.news.yahoo.com/reporter-justin-brake-mounting-charter-193432850.html|title=Reporter Justin Brake mounting charter challenge against Muskrat Falls charges|website=ca.news.yahoo.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref>  In November 2019 the Crown decided to drop the charge against Brake of unlawfully disobeying an order of the court, but decided to pursue a charge of mischief over $5,000. Judge Phyllis Harris will decide if the case proceeds. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/newfoundland-labrador/justin-brake-application-geoff-budden-1.5351309|title=Lawyer for Justin Brake asks judge to dismiss criminal charge against reporter|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brake, Justin}}\n[[Category:Canadian journalists]]\n[[Category:Canadian newspaper journalists]]\n[[Category:Freedom of the press by country]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Algonquin College alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "duplicate categorization; already in subcat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Justin_Brake_(journalist)"}
{"title_page": "Vijayaraghavan", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian actor}}\n{{for|the surname|Vijayaraghavan (surname)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{more footnotes|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Vijayaraghavan\n| image =Vijayaraghavan.jpg\n| caption =\n| native_name      = \u0d35\u0d3f\u0d1c\u0d2f\u0d30\u0d3e\u0d18\u0d35\u0d7b\n| native_name_lang = ml\n| birth_name = Narayanapillai Vijayaraghavan\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1951|01|12|df=yes}} <ref>http://cinidiary.com/peopleinfo.php?pigsection=Actor&picata=1&no_of_displayed_rows=4&no_of_rows_page=10&sletter=V</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[Federation of Malaya]]\n| nationality  = <!--Indian, Malaysian-->\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| othername =\n| occupation = Actor\n| yearsactive = 1973\u2013present\n| spouse = Suma\n| children = 2\n| father = [[N. N. Pillai]]\n| website =\n}}\n'''Vijayaraghavan''' is an Indian actor who mainly acts in [[Malayalam cinema]]. He is popular for his [[character actor|character roles]].<ref>http://www.manoramaonline.com/cgi-bin/MMOnline.dll/portal/ep/malayalamContentView.do?contentId=15294295&programId=1073752204&channelId=-1073750705&BV_ID=@@@&tabId=3</ref> He is the son of popular drama and cinema artist [[N. N. Pillai]].\n\n==Biography==\nVijayaraghavan made his film debut with ''Kaapaalika'', which was based on his father's play of the same name. He appeared in just a couple of scenes in this film. His opening as a full-fledged actor occurred ten years later in ''Surumayitta Kannukal'' (1983). However, it was only after he appeared in the 1987 film ''[[New Delhi (1987 film)|New Delhi]]'' that Vijayaraghavan became a busy star in Malayalam film.\n\nHe got a break with his performance in the 1989 film ''[[Ramji Rao Speaking]]'', in which he played the title role of the villain Ramji Rao. In the mid-1990s Vijayaraghavan played the hero in a number of low-budget Malayalam movies. He appeared in a few movies as second hero with Suresh Gopi in the lead role, including ''[[Commissioner (film)|Commissioner]]''. He also played notable roles in movies such as ''[[Ekalavyan (film)|Ekalavyan]]'', ''[[Crime File]]'', ''[[Mafia]]'' and ''King''. In 1995, he reprised his role as the character Ramji Rao in ''[[Mannar Mathai Speaking]]''.\n\nIn the 2000s, he turned to character and villain roles and appeared in various movies, among them ''[[C.I.D. Moosa]]'', ''[[Lion (2006 film)|Lion]]'', ''[[Chotta Mumbai]]'', ''[[Mayavi (2007 film)|Mayavi]]'', ''[[Bharathchandran I.P.S.]]'' and ''[[Raavanaprabhu]]''. He has also appeared in a popular Malayalam television serial entitled ''Kavyanjali'', produced by [[Balaji Telefilms]].\n\nVijayaraghavan is specially known for playing the iconic character Ramji Rao in 1989 film ''[[Ramji Rao Speaking]]'', in 1995 film ''[[Mannar Mathai Speaking]]'', in 2014 film ''[[Mannar Mathai Speaking 2]]'' and in 2019 film [[Mask (2019 film)]].\n\n==Personal life==\nVijayaraghavan is the son of veteran actor [[N. N. Pillai]] and Chinnamma. He was born in [[Kuala Lampur]], the capital of the [[Federation of Malaya]], where his father worked. He has two younger sisters, Sulochana and Renuka. He had his primary education from Govt. High School, Kudamaloor.<ref>http://www.mangalam.com/mangalam-varika/62478?page=0,1</ref>\n\nHe is married to Suma and has 2 sons. The elder son, Jinadevan is a businessman and is married to Rakhi. The younger son, Devadevan is in film industry. He is settled at Olassa, Kottayam District, Kerala.<ref>http://www.mangalam.com/mangalam-varika/62478</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n=== Malayalam films ===\n{{Div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*''[[Hridayam]]'' (2020)\n*''[[Sayanna Varthakal]]'' (2019)\n*'' Driving License'' (2019) as Kuttettan\n*'' Aadyarathri'' (2019)\n*'' [[Brother's Day]]'' (2019)\n*'' [[Porinju Mariam Jose]]'' (2019)\n*''[[Kakshi: Amminippilla]]'' (2019)\n*''[[Mask (2019 film)]]'' (2019) as Ramji Rao\n*''[[Soothrakkaran]]'' (2019)\n*''Mr and Mrs Rowdy'' (2019)\n*''Karinkannan'' (2018)\n*''Paviyettante Madhurachoodal'' (2018)\n*''Johny Johny Yes Appa'' (2018)\n*''Mangalyam Thanunanena'' (2018)\n*''[[Oru Pazhaya Bomb Kadha]]'' (2018) as Palathara Jose\n*''[[Aravindante Athidhikal]]'' (2018) as Kaala Prabhakaran\n*''Kammara Sambhavam'' (2018)\n*''Rosapoo'' (2018)\n*''[[Queen (2018 film)|Queen]]'' (2018) as Principal\n*''[[Carbon (2018 film)|Carbon]]'' (2018)\n* ''Aana Alaralodalaral'' (2017)\n* ''Punyalayan Private Limited'' (2017)\n*''Tharangam'' (2017)\n* ''[[Sherlock Toms]]'' (2017)  as Unnikrishnan<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ibtimes.co.in/sherlock-toms-review-by-audience-live-response-biju-menons-movie-743824|title=Sherlock Toms review by audience: Live response on Biju Menon's movie|last=James|first=Anu|work=International Business Times, India Edition|access-date=2018-10-15}}</ref>\n* [[Ramaleela (2017 film)|''Ramaleela'']] (2017) as Ambady Mohanan<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.manoramaonline.com/movies/exclusives/2017/10/07/ramaleela-vijayaraghavan-dileep.html|title=\u0d30\u0d3e\u0d2e\u0d32\u0d40\u0d32\u0d2f\u0d3f\u0d7d \u0d05\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d2d\u0d41\u0d24\u0d02 \u0d38\u0d02\u0d2d\u0d35\u0d3f\u0d1a\u0d4d\u0d1a\u0d41; \u0d35\u0d3f\u0d1c\u0d2f\u0d30\u0d3e\u0d18\u0d35\u0d7b|work=ManoramaOnline|access-date=2018-10-15}}</ref>\n*''Rakshadhikari Baiju'' (2017)\n* ''Sathya'' (2017)\n* [[Ezra (2017 film)|''Ezra'']] (2017)\n* ''[[James & Alice]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Leela (2016 film)|Leela]]'' (2016) as Gopinathan Pillai Nair/Pillechan<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/movie-review/leela-movie-review-this-ranjith-film-may-leave-you-confused/|title=Leela movie Review: This Ranjith film provokes disturbing questions|date=2016-04-23|work=The Indian Express|access-date=2018-10-15|language=en-US}}</ref>\n* ''[[Two Countries]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Loham]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Jilebi (2015 film)|Jilebi]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Oru Vadakkan Selfie]]'' (2015) Umesh's father\n* ''[[Bangalore Days]]'' (2014)