hapandavar'' (1999) as Balan\n* ''Rushy Vamsam'' (a.k.a. ''Rishi Vamsam'') (1999)\n* ''Tokyo Nagarathile Viseshangal'' (1999)\n* ''Alibabayum Arara Kallanmarum'' (1998) as Jayashankar\n* ''British Market'' (1998)\n* ''Dravidan'' (1998)\n* ''Harthal'' (1998)\n* ''Mandhri Kochamma'' (1998)\n* ''Mangamma'' (1998)\n* ''Poothiruvathiranalil'' (1998)\n* ''Adukkala Rahasyam Angadipattu'' (1997)\n* ''Desadanam'' (1997) as Sankaran\n* ''Kannoor'' (1997)\n* ''Adivaram'' (1997)\n* ''Kottapurathe Koottukudumbam'' (1997) as Sahadevan\n* ''Kudamattom'' (1997)\n* ''[[Harbour (film)|Harbour]]'' (1996) as Thommichan\n* ''[[Kanjirapally Kariyachan]]''(1996)\n* ''Naalamkettile Nalla Thambimar'' (1996)\n* ''Patanayakan'' (1996) as Pappan\n* ''Sulthan Hyderali'' (1996)\n* ''Rajaputhran'' (1996)\n* ''The King'' (1995) as Sanjay\n* ''Oru Abihibhashakante Case Diary'' (1995) as Balan\n* ''[[Highway (1995 film)|Highway]]'' (1995)\n* ''[[Mannar Mathai Speaking]]'' (1995) as Ramjirao\n* ''Radholsavam'' (1995)\n* ''Special Squad'' (1995) as Noufal\n* ''Sipayi Lahala'' (1995) as M.D.\n* ''Three Men Army'' (1995) as Rajesh\n* ''Thumboli Kadappuram'' (1995)\n* ''[[Cabinet (film)|Cabinet]]'' (1994) as Shivasankaran\n* ''Chukkan'' (1994) as Sreeni\n* ''Chief Minister K. R. Gowthami'' (1994)\n* ''Commissioner'' (a.k.a. ''Police Commissioner'') (1994) as Mohammad Iqbal\n* ''Kadal'' (1994) as Markose\n* ''Kambolam'' (1994)\n* ''Bhagyavan'' (1994)\n* ''Rudraksham'' (1994) as Jose\n* ''Sainyam'' (English title: ''The Army'') (1993)\n* ''Dhruvam'' (1993) as Ramdas\n* ''Aagneyam'' (1993) as Mammali\n* ''Bandhukkal Sathrukkal'' (1993)\n* ''Bhagyavan'' (1993) as Rahulan\n* ''Ekalavyan'' (1993) as Cheradi Skariah\n* ''Mafia'' (1993) as Sreeraman\n* ''Meleparambil Aanveedu'' (1993)\n* ''Porutham ''(1993)\n* ''Sthalathe Pradhana Payyans'' (1993) as Jayapalan\n* ''Vietnam Colony'' (1993) as Vattappalli\n* ''Aardram'' (1992) as Madhavan\n* ''Ellarum Chollanu'' (1992)\n* ''Kaazhchakkppuram'' (1992) as Sethumadhavan\n* ''Manyanmaar'' (1992)\n* ''Sathyaprathingna'' (1992)\n* ''Police Diary'' (1992)\n* ''Cheppu Kilukkunna Changathi'' (1991) as Ashok Kartha\n* ''Georgekutty C/O Georgekutty'' (1991) as Goonda\n* ''Kuttapathram'' (1991) as Sethu\n* ''[[Oru Prathyeka Ariyippu]]'' (1991) as Vishnu\n* ''Nattuvishesham''(1991) as Vijayan\n* ''Thudarkadha'' (1991) as Sudhakaran\n* ''Nettippattam'' (1991) as Sugunan\n* ''Onnam Muhurtham'' (1991) as William Patrick Parera\n* ''Kadalora Kattu'' (1991) as Ponnappan\n* ''Parallel College'' (1991) as Chandrashekharan Nair\n* ''Samrajyam'' (1990) as Khadir\n* ''Appu'' (1990) as Ramankutty\n* ''Dr. Pasupathy'' (1990) as Thomas\n* ''Indrajaalam'' (1990) as Thankappan\n* ''[[Nagarangalil Chennu Raparkam]]'' (1990)\n* ''Nammude Naadu'' (1990) as Balan\n* ''Nanma Niranjavan Srinivasan'' (1990)\n* ''Orukkam'' (1990) as Ramu\n* ''Purappadu'' (1990)\n* ''Prosecution'' (1990)\n* ''Pradesika Varthakal'' (1989) as Ramu\n* ''Mahayanam'' (1989) as Sunnychan\n* ''Adikkurippu'' (1989\n* ''Kali karyamaai: Crime Branch''(1989) as Babu\n* ''Douthyam'' (1989) as Capt. Rajiv Kumar\n* ''Kaalal Pada'' (1989)\n* ''Swantham Ennu Karuthi'' (1989)\n* ''Miss Pamela'' (1989)\n* ''Naaduvazhikal'' (1989) as Police Superintendent\n* ''News'' (1989) as Freddy Issac\n* ''[[Ramji Rao Speaking]]'' (1989) as Ramjirao\n* ''Oru CBI Diary Kurippu'' (1988) as Johny\n* ''Dinarathrangal'' (1988)\n* ''Puravrutham'' (1988) as Abu\n* ''[[1921 (1988 film)|1921]]'' (1988)\n* ''Moonnam Mura'' (1988) as Karunan\n* ''Witness'' (1988) as Usthad Hamsa\n* ''New Delhi'' (1987) as Ananthan\n* ''Naradhan Keralathil'' (1987) as Khader\n* ''P.C. 369'' (1987) as Johny's brother\n* ''Manasilloru Manimuthu'' (1986)\n* ''Njan Kathorthirikkum'' (1986)\n* ''Ee Sabdam Innathe Sabdam'' (1985) as Balu\n* ''Uyarukm Njan Nadaake'' (1985)\n* ''[[Pinnilavu]]'' (a.k.a. ''Pinninvalu'') (1983) as Wilson\n* ''Surumayitta Kannukal'' (1983)\n* ''Aana'' (1983)\n* ''Innalenkil Nale'' (1982)\n* ''Ammakorumma'' (1981) as Gopakumar\n* ''Picnic'' (1975)\n* ''Kaapaalika'' (1973) as Babu\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Tamil films===\n {| class=\"wikitable sortable\" cellpadding=\"6\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! Year !! Film !! Role !!Director \n|-\n| 1990 || ''[[Arangetra Velai]]''||Pakkiram||[[Fazil (director)|Fazil]]\n|-\n| 2011 || ''[[Venghai]]''||Minister Juddhism||[[Hari (director)|Hari]]\n|-\n| 2017 ||  ''[[Bairavaa]]''||Vaishali's Father||[[Bharathan (Tamil director)|Bharathan]]\n\n|}\n\n==Television serial==\n*Crime Branch (Kairali TV)\n*Kaavyanjali.(Surya TV)\n*Snehatheeram(Surya TV )\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160304034748/http://en.msidb.org/displayProfile.php?category=actors&artist=Vijayaraghavan&limit=184 Vijayaraghavan at MSI]\n* {{IMDb name|id=1066795|name=Vijayaraghavan}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vijayaraghavan}}\n[[Category:21st-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Kerala]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Malayalam cinema]]\n[[Category:Indian male film actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian actor}}\n{{for|the surname|Vijayaraghavan (surname)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{more footnotes|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Vijayaraghavan\n| image =Vijayaraghavan.jpg\n| caption =\n| native_name      = \u0d35\u0d3f\u0d1c\u0d2f\u0d30\u0d3e\u0d18\u0d35\u0d7b\n| native_name_lang = ml\n| birth_name = Narayanapillai Vijayaraghavan\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1951|01|12|df=yes}} <ref>http://cinidiary.com/peopleinfo.php?pigsection=Actor&picata=1&no_of_displayed_rows=4&no_of_rows_page=10&sletter=V</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[Federation of Malaya]]\n| nationality  = <!--Indian, Malaysian-->\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| othername =\n| occupation = Actor\n| yearsactive = 1973\u2013present\n| spouse = Suma\n| children = 2\n| father = [[N. N. Pillai]]\n| website =\n}}\n'''Vijayaraghavan''' is an Indian actor who mainly acts in [[Malayalam cinema]]. He is popular for his [[character actor|character roles]].<ref>http://www.manoramaonline.com/cgi-bin/MMOnline.dll/portal/ep/malayalamContentView.do?contentId=15294295&programId=1073752204&channelId=-1073750705&BV_ID=@@@&tabId=3</ref> He is the son of popular drama and cinema artist [[N. N. Pillai]].\n\n==Biography==\nVijayaraghavan made his film debut with ''Kaapaalika'', which was based on his father's play of the same name. He appeared in just a couple of scenes in this film. His opening as a full-fledged actor occurred ten years later in ''Surumayitta Kannukal'' (1983). However, it was only after he appeared in the 1987 film ''[[New Delhi (1987 film)|New Delhi]]'' that Vijayaraghavan became a busy star in Malayalam film.\n\nHe got a break with his performance in the 1989 film ''[[Ramji Rao Speaking]]'', in which he played the title role of the villain Ramji Rao. In the mid-1990s Vijayaraghavan played the hero in a number of low-budget Malayalam movies. He appeared in a few movies as second hero with Suresh Gopi in the lead role, including ''[[Commissioner (film)|Commissioner]]''. He also played notable roles in movies such as ''[[Ekalavyan (film)|Ekalavyan]]'', ''[[Crime File]]'', ''[[Mafia]]'' and ''King''. In 1995, he reprised his role as the character Ramji Rao in ''[[Mannar Mathai Speaking]]''.\n\nIn the 2000s, he turned to character and villain roles and appeared in various movies, among them ''[[C.I.D. Moosa]]'', ''[[Lion (2006 film)|Lion]]'', ''[[Chotta Mumbai]]'', ''[[Mayavi (2007 film)|Mayavi]]'', ''[[Bharathchandran I.P.S.]]'' and ''[[Raavanaprabhu]]''. He has also appeared in a popular Malayalam television serial entitled ''Kavyanjali'', produced by [[Balaji Telefilms]].\n\nVijayaraghavan is specially known for playing the iconic character Ramji Rao in 1989 film ''[[Ramji Rao Speaking]]'', in 1995 film ''[[Mannar Mathai Speaking]]'', in 2014 film ''[[Mannar Mathai Speaking 2]]'' and in 2019 film [[Mask (2019 film)]].\n\n==Personal life==\nVijayaraghavan is the son of veteran actor [[N. N. Pillai]] and Chinnamma. He was born in [[Kuala Lampur]], the capital of the [[Federation of Malaya]], where his father worked. He has two younger sisters, Sulochana and Renuka. He had his primary education from Govt. High School, Kudamaloor.<ref>http://www.mangalam.com/mangalam-varika/62478?page=0,1</ref>\n\nHe is married to Suma and has 2 sons. The elder son, Jinadevan is a businessman and is married to Rakhi. The younger son, Devadevan is in film industry. He is settled at Olassa, Kottayam District, Kerala.<ref>http://www.mangalam.com/mangalam-varika/62478</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n=== Malayalam films ===\n{{Div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*''[[Hridayam]]'' (2020)\n*''[[Sayanna Varthakal]]'' (2019)\n*'' Driving License'' (2019) as Kuttettan\n*'' Aadyarathri'' (2019)\n*'' [[Brother's Day]]'' (2019)\n*'' [[Porinju Mariam Jose]]'' (2019)\n*''[[Kakshi: Amminippilla]]'' (2019)\n*''[[Mask (2019 film)]]'' (2019) as Ramji Rao\n*''[[Soothrakkaran]]'' (2019)\n*''Mr and Mrs Rowdy'' (2019)\n*''Karinkannan'' (2018)\n*''Paviyettante Madhurachoodal'' (2018)\n*''Johny Johny Yes Appa'' (2018)\n*''Mangalyam Thanunanena'' (2018)\n*''[[Oru Pazhaya Bomb Kadha]]'' (2018) as Palathara Jose\n*''[[Aravindante Athidhikal]]'' (2018) as Kaala Prabhakaran\n*''Kammara Sambhavam'' (2018)\n*''Rosapoo'' (2018)\n*''[[Queen (2018 film)|Queen]]'' (2018) as Principal\n*''[[Carbon (2018 film)|Carbon]]'' (2018)\n* ''Aana Alaralodalaral'' (2017)\n* ''Punyalayan Private Limited'' (2017)\n*''Tharangam'' (2017)\n* ''[[Sherlock Toms]]'' (2017)  as Unnikrishnan<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ibtimes.co.in/sherlock-toms-review-by-audience-live-response-biju-menons-movie-743824|title=Sherlock Toms review by audience: Live response on Biju Menon's movie|last=James|first=Anu|work=Int